'''Janu Sirsasana''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|dʒ|ɑː|n|uː|_|ʃ|ər|ˈ|ʃ|ɑː|s|ɑː|n|ɑː}} {{respell|JAH|noo|_|shər|SHAH|sah|nah}}<ref>{{cite book |last1=Budilovsky |first1=Joan |last2=Adamson |first2=Eve |title=The complete idiot's guide to yoga |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b5pE8-Oyly0C |accessdate=11 April 2011 |edition=2 |year=2000 |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-02-863970-3 |page=210}}</ref> {{lang-sa|जानु शीर्षासन}}; [[IAST]]: ''jānu śīrṣāsana'' {{IPA-sa|dʑaːnu ɕiːrʂaːsənə|}}), '''Head-to-Knee Pose''',<ref> {{cite web | url = http://www.ashtangayoga.info/practice/asana-vinyasa-series/primary-series-yoga-chikitsa/item/janu-shirshasana-a/ | title = Janu Shirshasana A - AshtangaYoga.info | accessdate = 2011-04-09 | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110817021247/http://www.ashtangayoga.info/practice/asana-vinyasa-series/primary-series-yoga-chikitsa/item/janu-shirshasana-a/ | archivedate = 2011-08-17 | df = }}</ref><ref name="Long2011">{{cite book |last=Long |first=Ray |title=Yoga Mat Companion 2: Anatomy for Hip Openers and Forward Bends |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sQnNCuCEv6QC&pg=PA114 |accessdate=9 April 2011 |date=22 January 2011 |publisher=Greenleaf Book (Distributor) |isbn=978-1-60743-942-4 |page=114}}</ref><ref name="FishmanSmall2007">{{cite book |last1=Fishman |first1=Loren Martin |last2=Small |first2=Eric |title=Yoga and Multiple Sclerosis: A Journey to Health and Healing |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VJjoQ1ih48sC&pg=PA86 |accessdate=9 April 2011 |date=20 June 2007 |publisher=Demos Medical Publishing |isbn=978-1-932603-17-0 |page=86}}</ref><ref name="Long2009">{{cite book |last=Long |first=Ray |title=The Key Poses of Yoga: The Scientific Keys, Volume II |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4BubtZgBefkC&pg=PA99 |accessdate=9 April 2011 |date=August 2009 |publisher=Greenleaf Book (Distributor) |isbn=978-1-60743-239-5 |page=100}}</ref> '''Head-to-Knee Forward Bend''',<ref> {{cite web | url = http://www.yogajournal.com/poses/476 | title = Yoga Journal - Head-to-Knee Forward Bend | accessdate = 2011-04-09}}</ref> '''Head of the Knee Pose''',<ref name="Inc.1988">{{cite book |author=Active Interest Media, Inc. |title=Yoga Journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6esDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35 |accessdate=9 April 2011 |date=November 1988 |publisher=Active Interest Media, Inc. |page=35}}</ref><ref name="Inc.1982">{{cite book |author=Active Interest Media, Inc. |title=Yoga Journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4usDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42 |accessdate=9 April 2011 |date=March 1982 |publisher=Active Interest Media, Inc. |page=42}}</ref> or '''Head-on-Knee Pose'''<ref name="RamaswamiHurwitz2006">{{cite book |last1=Ramaswami |first1=Srivatsa |last2=Hurwitz |first2=David |title=Yoga Beneath the Surface: An American Student and His Indian Teacher Discuss Yoga Philosophy and Practice |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jTcLbUgUoyMC&pg=PA88 |accessdate=9 April 2011 |date=13 June 2006 |publisher=Da Capo Press |isbn=978-1-56924-294-0 |page=88}}</ref> is an [[asana]]. It is part of the [[Ashtanga Vinyasa Yoga|Ashtanga Yoga]] Primary Series and is commonly practiced as a seated asana in many styles of yoga.
==Etymology== The name comes from the Sanskrit words ''janu'' (जानु, jānu) meaning "knee", ''shirsha'' (शीर्ष, śīrṣa) meaning "head", and ''āsana'' (आसन) meaning "posture" or "seat".<ref> {{cite web | url = http://de.ashtangayoga.info/praxis/primary-series-yoga-chikitsa/item/janu-shirshasana-a/| title = Janu Shirshasana A - AshtangaYoga.info | accessdate = 2011-04-09}}</ref> Although it bears a similar name, Janu Sirsanana bears little resemblance to [[Sirsasana]] ([[Headstand]]).
==Description== In a seated position, one leg is extended with toes pointing upward, and the other leg is bent with knee pointing away from the straight leg and the sole of the foot in by the groin. The torso turns and folds over the extended leg.
Janu Sirsasana is a spinal twist, as well as a forward fold. The potential is to free up constriction in different parts of the back and to loosen the hamstrings.
Janu Sirsasana differs from [[Paschimottanasana]] in its asymmetry in the legs and hips, and in the twisting action this asana imparts to the spine.
